3–Male":"1453–Deceased","1455–1514":"1455–1514","1400–Male":"1400–Deceased","1395–1452":"1395–1452","1514":"1514","1457":"1457","1400":"1400","1455":"1455","1454":"1454","1453":"1453","1452":"1452","about 1455":"about 1455","1395":"1395","1438":"1438","Putney, London, England":"Putney, London, England","Norwell, Nottinghamshire, England":"Norwell, Nottinghamshire, England","Putney, Surrey, England":"Putney, Surrey, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Glossop","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from Glossop in Derbyshire."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Sir","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From Old Norse, originally a byname meaning ‘bride, wife’; in mythology the name of Thor's golden-haired wife."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Nicolas","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From Late Greek.  See  <b>Nicholas</b> ."],"variants":[{"name":"Nicholas","meanings":["form of the post-classical Greek personal name <i>Nikolaos</i>, derived from <i>nikē</i> ‘victory’ + <i>laos</i> ‘people’. The spelling with <i>-ch-</i> first occurred as early as the 12th century, and became firmly established at the time of the Reformation, although  <b>Nicolas</b>  is still occasionally found.  St Nicholas  was a 4th-century bishop of Myra in Lycia, about whom virtually nothing factual is known, although a vast body of legend grew up around him, and he became the patron saint of Greece and of Russia, as well as of children, sailors, merchants, and pawnbrokers. His feast day is  6 December , and among the many roles which legend has assigned to him is that of bringer of Christmas presents, in the guise of ‘Santa Claus’ (an alteration of the Dutch form of his name, <i>Sinterklaas</i>)."]},{"name":"Nicolao","meanings":["form of the post-classical Greek personal name <i>Nikolaos</i>, derived from <i>nikē</i> ‘victory’ + <i>laos</i> ‘people’. The spelling with <i>-ch-</i> first occurred as early as the 12th century, and became firmly established at the time of the Reformation, although  <b>Nicolas</b>  is still occasionally found.  St Nicholas  was a 4th-century bishop of Myra in Lycia, about whom virtually nothing factual is known, although a vast body of legend grew up around him, and he became the patron saint of Greece and of Russia, as well as of children, sailors, merchants, and pawnbrokers. His feast day is  6 December , and among the many roles which legend has assigned to him is that of bringer of Christmas presents, in the guise of ‘Santa Claus’ (an alteration of the Dutch form of his name, <i>Sinterklaas</i>)."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705197,"age":17,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir Nicolas Glossop was born in 1438, in Putney, Surrey, England, United Kingdom, his father, Sir Nicholas Glossop, was 39 and his mother, Joan Elizabeth Bagot, was 43. He married Lady Catherine Elizabeth Wirksworth in 1454, in Norwell, Nottinghamshire, England. They were the parents of at least 1 son and 1 daughter. He died in 1514, in Putney, London, England, at the age of 76."},"et":{"1438–1514":"1438–1514","1438–1457":"1438–1457","1453–Male":"1453–Surnud","1455–1514":"1455–1514","1400–Male":"1400–Surnud","1395–1452":"1395–1452","1514":"1514","1457":"1457","1400":"1400","1455":"1455","1454":"1454","1453":"1453","1452":"1